Bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil with @salt{1/2%tsp} for the pasta.

Trim the @courgette{1}(trimmed and sliced into thick 1cm rounds). Trim and thinly slice the @spring onion{1}(trimmed and thinly sliced).

Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2}(peeled and grated). Grate the @mature cheddar cheese{30%g}(grated).

Heat a large #frying pan{} on high heat (no oil).

Once hot, add the courgette and cook until starting to char, ~{2-3%minutes} each side.

Transfer to a clean #chopping board{} or #plate{} and allow to cool.

When your pan of water is boiling, add the @linguine{180%g} and bring back to the boil. Cook until tender, ~{12%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #colander{}.

Pop back into the pan, drizzle with @oil{} and stir through to stop it sticking together.

Meanwhile, put the (now empty) frying pan on medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{}.

Once hot, add the @garlic{2%cloves}(peeled and grated) and a pinch of @chilli flakes{1%pinch} (use less if you'd prefer things milder - add more later if you'd like) and cook, stirring, for ~{1%minute}.

Stir in the @tomato passata{1}, @sun-dried tomato paste{25%g}, @vegetable stock paste{10%g} and @water for the sauce{75%ml}. Bring to the boil and simmer until thickened, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Once thickened, stir the @king prawns{300%g} into the tomato sauce and cook for ~{5-6%minutes}. IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw prawns. The prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

Meanwhile, roughly chop the charred courgette rounds.

In a small #bowl{}, mix together the chopped courgette, spring onion and a pinch of @chilli flakes{1%pinch} (use less if you'd prefer things milder).

Add the cooked pasta, cheese and half the charred courgette mixture to the sauce.

Mix well to combine, then season to taste with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Add a splash of water if it's a little thick.

Share the prawn linguine between your bowls, then spoon over the remaining charred courgette mixture to finish.

Enjoy!